<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO &quot;DON'T UNDERSTAND&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 13:20:20 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Tim, you bring up some good points.  It is hard to understand at this date, because a lot of the events of the time have been put aside.  The two driving forces, it seems to me, for the attitudes of the American public at the time I came home (1971) from Vietnam were the civil rights movement and the tragedies of the war.  Civil rights showcased the divide in this nation by &quot;race&quot; and the tragedies included both the Kent State shootings of protesters by the National Guard and the Mia Lai massacre by the U.S. Army of Vietnamese civilians.  <br><br>
I have addressed some of this in the other dialog on &quot;Maya Lin and Racism,&quot; in which I related some instances of racism I had experienced.  <br><br>
Concerning the anger and indifference of the American public toward returning GIs, there was an organized attempt to demonstrate these feelings against GI's at airports and terminals where we returned.  Much of this perception by the returning GIs has to do with these demonstrations, and the complacent attitude of American public.<br><br>
I have two other thoughts.  First, I think the Nixon administration did much for the GIs in the field, but was extremely negligent in explaining their actions at home; at times they lied to the American public about the actions occurring in Vietnam, and this really turned the public off concerning their feelings about returning GIs.  <br><br>
Second, and perhaps more importantly, this was the first television war.  People saw first hand what happened when a plane dropped napalm on a village, and what the human cost was to that.  This may contribute to the perception that this was the &quot;most horrific war&quot; we have fought in.  But a reading of Clive Cussler's &quot;The Sea Hunters,&quot; which documents the re-discovery of many of the USA Civil War wrecks and gives dramatic accounts of their sinkings reveals that this war was also very horrific.<br><br>
A &quot;parrallel war&quot; in Cambodia was going on at the same time, and I would recommend a book by John M. Del Vecchio entitled &quot;FOR THE SAKE OF ALL LIVING THINGS&quot; if anyone wishes to get a real feeling for what was happening in that country.  The book jacket says &quot;In this unflinching and unforgettable epic saga, Del Vecchio re-creates the violence and horror of Viet Nam's parallel tragedy - the Cambodian holocaust - as seen through the eyees of a Cambodian family and the American adviser whose fate becomes irrevocably linked with theirs.  A sweeping tale of savagery and survival that pits parents and children against both the North Viet Namese invaders and the unprecedented ferocity of the Khmer Rouge, &quot;For the Sake of All Living Things&quot; is an unrelenting, ultimately inspiring chronicle of conflict and redemption in the killing fields.&quot;  <br><br>
For any former protesters out there, I would ask that you take the time to read this book.  It was my hardest read, but it is a must to gain an understanding of the situation in SE Asia in the late 1960's and early 1970's.  If a protester of the war can get through this reading without a change in perception concerning these wars, (s)he has a better stomach than mine.<br><br>
I think that the intermingling of all of these conflicts contributes to the thought that this was the &quot;most horrific&quot; of our wars.  
